\title{12 Factor App Modernization}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{}

\meta{description}{Systematic process for analyzing and modernizing legacy applications to comply with the 12-Factor App methodology. Covers code analysis, configuration externalization, dependency management, and container/Kubernetes best practices.}

\subtree{
\title{12-Factor App Modernization}
\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\subtree{
\title{Analyze Application}
\pre{\startverb
# Clone repository
git clone <repo-url>
cd <repo-name>

# Create inventory of services
# Document tech stack, deployment configs, backing services
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Generate Compliance Report}
\p{Create a structured JSON report documenting compliance status for all 12 factors.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{The 12 Factors}
\pre{\startverb
| Factor | Principle | Key Questions |
|--------|-----------|---------------|
| I. Codebase | One codebase, many deploys | Is there a single repo? Are there environment-specific branches? |
| II. Dependencies | Explicitly declare and isolate | Are all dependencies declared with pinned versions? |
| III. Config | Store config in environment | Are connection strings, credentials, and settings externalized? |
| IV. Backing Services | Treat as attached resources | Can backing services be swapped without code changes? |
| V. Build, Release, Run | Strict separation | Are build artifacts immutable? Is config injected at runtime? |
| VI. Processes | Stateless processes | Is session state stored externally? |
| VII. Port Binding | Export via port binding | Are services self-contained with embedded servers? |
| VIII. Concurrency | Scale via process model | Can the app scale horizontally? |
| IX. Disposability | Fast startup, graceful shutdown | Does the app handle SIGTERM? Is there an init system (tini)? |
| X. Dev/Prod Parity | Keep environments similar | Are dev and prod using same backing services? |
| XI. Logs | Treat as event streams | Does the app write to stdout/stderr? |
| XII. Admin Processes | Run as one-off processes | Are migrations and admin tasks separate from the main app? |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Application Analysis}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Clone and Inventory}
\p{Map out the application architecture:}

\ul{
\li{Identify all services/microservices}
\li{Document the tech stack for each service (language, framework, runtime)}
\li{List all deployment configurations (Dockerfiles, docker-compose, Kubernetes manifests)}
\li{Identify backing services (databases, caches, message queues)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Analyze Against Each Factor}
\p{Systematically evaluate each service against all 12 factors. Create a structured report documenting compliance status.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Compliance Report Structure}
\pre{\startverb
{
  "title": "12-Factor App Compliance Report",
  "repository": "<repo-url>",
  "analysis_date": "<date>",
  "summary": {
    "total_factors": 12,
    "services_analyzed": ["<service-list>"],
    "overall_compliance": "<status>"
  },
  "factors": {
    "<factor_id>": {
      "name": "<factor-name>",
      "status": "<COMPLIANT|PARTIAL|NON-COMPLIANT>",
      "findings": ["<observations>"],
      "issues": [{"service": "", "file": "", "problem": "", "severity": "", "impact": ""}],
      "fixes": [{"service": "", "file": "", "action": ""}]
    }
  },
  "priority_fixes": [{"priority": 1, "category": "", "description": "", "affected_files": []}]
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Configuration Externalization (Factor III - Highest Priority)}
\p{This is typically the most critical violation. Hardcoded credentials and connection strings are security risks.}

\subtree{
\title{Python (Flask/Django)}
\pre{\startverb
# Before (hardcoded)
redis = Redis(host="redis", port=6379)

# After (externalized)
redis_host = os.getenv('REDIS_HOST', 'redis')
redis_port = int(os.getenv('REDIS_PORT', '6379'))
redis = Redis(host=redis_host, port=redis_port)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Node.js}
\pre{\startverb
// Before (hardcoded)
const pool = new Pool({
  connectionString: 'postgres://user:pass@db/mydb'
});

// After (externalized)
const pool = new Pool({
  connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL || 'postgres://user:pass@db/mydb'
});
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{C#/.NET}
\pre{\startverb
// Before (hardcoded)
var conn = new NpgsqlConnection("Server=db;Username=postgres;Password=secret;");

// After (externalized)
var host = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DB_HOST") ?? "db";
var user = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DB_USER") ?? "postgres";
var password = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DB_PASSWORD") ?? "postgres";
var connString = $"Server={host};Username={user};Password={password};";
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Dependency Management (Factor II)}
\p{Unpinned dependencies cause reproducibility issues and potential security vulnerabilities.}

\subtree{
\title{Python (requirements.txt)}
\pre{\startverb
# Before
Flask
Redis
gunicorn

# After
Flask==3.0.0
Redis==5.0.1
gunicorn==21.2.0
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Node.js (package.json)}
\pre{\startverb
// Before - caret allows minor/patch updates
"dependencies": {
  "express": "^4.18.2"
}

// After - exact versions
"dependencies": {
  "express": "4.18.2"
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Important:} After changing package.json versions, regenerate package-lock.json:}

\pre{\startverb
rm package-lock.json && npm install --package-lock-only
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Signal Handling (Factor IX)}
\p{Containers need proper init systems to handle signals correctly for graceful shutdown.}

\subtree{
\title{Add tini to Dockerfiles}
\pre{\startverb
# Install tini
RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends tini && \
    rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# Use tini as entrypoint
ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/bin/tini", "--"]
CMD ["your-app-command"]
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Docker Compose Configuration}
\p{Replace hardcoded values with environment variable substitution:}

\pre{\startverb
services:
  app:
    environment:
      DATABASE_URL: "postgres://${POSTGRES_USER:-postgres}:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD:-postgres}@db/mydb"
      REDIS_HOST: redis
  
  db:
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: "${POSTGRES_USER:-postgres}"
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: "${POSTGRES_PASSWORD:-postgres}"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Kubernetes Secrets}
\p{Never store credentials in plain text in Kubernetes manifests.}

\subtree{
\title{Create Secret Manifest}
\pre{\startverb
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: db-credentials
type: Opaque
stringData:
  POSTGRES_USER: postgres
  POSTGRES_PASSWORD: <generate-strong-password>
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reference in Deployments}
\pre{\startverb
env:
- name: DB_PASSWORD
  valueFrom:
    secretKeyRef:
      name: db-credentials
      key: POSTGRES_PASSWORD
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Validation}
\subtree{
\title{Docker Compose Validation}
\pre{\startverb
docker compose config --quiet && echo "✓ Valid"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Kubernetes Manifest Validation}
\pre{\startverb
kubectl apply --dry-run=client -f k8s-specifications/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Build and Test}
\pre{\startverb
docker compose build
docker compose up -d
docker compose ps  # Verify all services healthy
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Anti-Patterns}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Hardcoded connection strings} - Most common and most critical}
\li{\strong{Unpinned dependencies} - Causes "works on my machine" issues}
\li{\strong{Missing init systems} - Causes zombie processes and slow shutdowns}
\li{\strong{Credentials in source control} - Security vulnerability}
\li{\strong{Environment-specific code branches} - Violates codebase principle}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Environment Variable Naming Conventions}
\p{Use consistent, descriptive names:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb DB_HOST\stopverb}, \code{\startverb DB_PORT\stopverb}, \code{\startverb DB_USER\stopverb}, \code{\startverb DB_PASSWORD\stopverb}, \code{\startverb DB_NAME\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb REDIS_HOST\stopverb}, \code{\startverb REDIS_PORT\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb DATABASE_URL\stopverb} (for connection string format)}
\li{\code{\startverb <SERVICE>_URL\stopverb} for full connection strings}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Backward Compatibility}
\p{Always provide sensible defaults when externalizing config:}

\pre{\startverb
# Maintains backward compatibility with existing deployments
host = os.getenv('REDIS_HOST', 'redis')  # Falls back to 'redis'
\stopverb}
}

